        "title": "Covenant land-seizure as decalogue violation — the specific charge (2:1-2)",
        "range": "2:1-2",
        "excerpt": "They covet fields and then seize them, and houses, and take them away. They rob a man and his house, a man and his inheritance.",
        "body": "The woe-oracle (*hoy*) in verse 1 is the Hebrew equivalent of a death announcement — funeral vocabulary pronounced over the living to signal that their end is already determined. Micah uses it to announce the verdict before the evidence. What follows in verse 2 is the evidence, and it is legally precise.\n\nThe verb *chamad* (covet) is the exact term of the Tenth Commandment in both Exodus 20:17 and Deuteronomy 5:21. Micah is not using loose prophetic language; he is citing the decalogue. The schemers are Tenth Commandment violators who have escalated from internal desire to external seizure (*gazal*, to seize by force or fraud), from a prohibited wish to a prohibited act. The entire progression of Exodus 20's commandments — from murder through adultery through theft through false witness to covetousness — converges here: these men have violated the final commandment's root (desire), the eighth commandment's act (theft), and the sixth commandment's spirit (treating a neighbor's life as expendable).\n\nThe word *nachalah* (inheritance) is the chapter's most theologically loaded noun. Under the Mosaic land-tenure system (Leviticus 25; Numbers 27; 36), each family's ancestral allotment was inalienable — it could not be permanently sold, and if lost had to be returned in the Year of Jubilee. The land belonged ultimately to Yahweh (Leviticus 25:23: 'the land is Mine'), and Israelites held it as resident aliens under His tenure. Seizing a *nachalah* was therefore not only theft from a neighbor but the usurpation of God's property. The canonical parallel is exact: Ahab's seizure of Naboth's vineyard in 1 Kings 21, which Elijah prosecuted with almost identical language and which ended in the total destruction of Ahab's dynasty.\n\nThe note that they scheme by night but execute by morning (2:1) carries a theological freight beyond the portrait of calculated sin. Charles Spurgeon observed that the darkness of planning and the daylight of execution expose the schemers' lack of shame — they are not even embarrassed by their own deeds. What ought to require darkness is done in full public view because institutional power has replaced moral conscience.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chashav aven* (devise iniquity) — *chashav* is the craftsman's word for skilled planning, used of Bezalel constructing the tabernacle (Exodus 31:4) and of weavers calculating patterns. Sin here is artisanal: skilled, intentional, executed with craft. *Chamad* is the identical root as the Tenth Commandment's prohibition. *Nachalah* — from *nachal*, to possess as an inheritance — is the primary term for the divinely-distributed covenant estate."
